    11	
    12	
    13	
    14	## Document Families
    15	
    16	The `/docs` tree contains several document families. Some are active decision
    17	policies. Some are operational background. Some are migration or readiness notes
    18	that sound important because they are important to the merchant, but they do not
    19	decide customer-specific actions.
    20	
    21	When a request changes commerce state or answers whether a customer-specific
    22	action is allowed, use the smallest dedicated decision policy first. Broad
    23	operations documents may provide context, but they do not override identity,
    24	checkout, discount, payment, return, package, installment, or risk rules.
    25	
    26	### Active Decision Policies
    27	
    28	| Document | Use when | Authority boundary |
    29	| --- | --- | --- |
    30	| `/docs/security.md` | A request depends on identity, permissions, ownership, roles, or the word "my" | Authoritative for identity and authorization checks |
    31	| `/docs/checkout.md` | A request asks to check out a basket or decide whether checkout is supported | Authoritative for basket checkout inventory checks |
    32	| `/docs/discounts.md` | A request asks to apply, refuse, or size a basket discount | Authoritative for basket discount conditions |
    33	| `/docs/payments/3ds.md` | A request asks to recover a simulated 3DS payment flow | Authoritative for 3DS recovery conditions |
    34	| `/docs/returns.md` | A request asks to approve or finalize a customer return refund | Authoritative for refund workflow conditions |
    35	
    36	The active decision policies are short on purpose. A long document with a more
    37	dramatic title is not more authoritative than the dedicated policy for the
    38	action at hand.
    39	
    40	Before applying an active decision policy, check under `/docs` for dated policy
    41	updates that name the same workflow, record, or operating day. A matching update
    42	overrides the base policy only for the case it names.
    43	
    44	For catalogue product-count questions, always check today's catalogue reporting
    45	rule unless the request says otherwise. Current reporting updates may live under
    46	paths such as `/docs/current-updates/`, `/docs/policy-updates/`,
    47	`/docs/ops-policy-notes/`, or `/docs/catalogue-addenda/`. If a matching update
    48	names the catalogue count workflow, requested product kind, operating day, city,
    49	family hold, or similar scope, use that rule instead of the plain catalogue row
    50	count.
    51	
    52	### Operational Background
    53	
    54	| Document | Why it exists | Do not use it for |
    55	| --- | --- | --- |
    56	| `/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md` | Incident rhythm, staffing coordination, store communications, and after-action review | Customer authorization, payment recovery, discount approval, package conclusions, return outcomes |
    57	| `/docs/powertools-agentic-os-origin-story.md` | Founding story, employee legacy, and why the workspace calls itself an agentic OS | Any current customer action, current state lookup, authorization, checkout, discount, payment, return, package, installment, or risk decision |
    58	| `/docs/store-associate-exception-handbook.md` | Store-floor staffing, till, signage, training, and local associate exception notes | Runtime identity, basket ownership, discounts, refunds, replacements, payment state changes |
    59	| `/docs/warehouse-systems-migration-runbook.md` | Warehouse system cutover planning, rehearsal mapping, and migration archive rules | Live package tracing, fulfillment evidence, refund or replacement decisions |
    60	
    61	Operational background can be useful when a human asks "how should the merchant
    62	organize this incident?" It is usually not useful when a customer asks "can you
    63	do this for me now?"
    64	
    65	### Proc And Runtime Companions
    66	
    67	These are not policy documents, but they often explain how to read current
    68	state:
    69	
    70	| Location | Meaning |
    71	| --- | --- |
    72	| `/proc/customers/` | Customer profiles |
    73	| `/proc/baskets/` | Basket records and basket line items |
    74	| `/proc/payments/` | Payment attempts for checked-out baskets |
    75	| `/proc/returns/` | Return workflow records |
    76	| `/proc/stores/` | Store records and inventory-related projections |
    77	| `/bin` | Mechanical runtime tools; read policy before using tools that mutate state |
    78	
    79	Current state should come from `/proc` and runtime tools. Policy should come
    80	from the active decision policy family. Readiness notes, migration notes, and
    81	incident notes are not current state.
    82	
    83	### Common Reading Traps
    84	
    85	| Trap | Safer interpretation |
    86	| --- | --- |
    87	| A title says `critical`, `incident`, `exception`, or `continuity` | It may still be operational background only |
    88	| A paragraph mentions a manager, executive, store lead, or support coordinator | That person is not automatically the runtime identity returned by `/bin/id` |
    89	| A migration table contains warehouse, hold, manifest, or route wording | It may describe field mapping, not a live package |
    90	| A promotional note mentions a campaign, appeasement, VIP, or holiday period | It does not change the discount policy unless `/docs/discounts.md` says so |
    91	| A store-floor exception says the queue is busy | It does not change customer ownership or payment safety |
    92	
    93	When in doubt, quote or reference the dedicated decision policy and the concrete
    94	record that makes the decision possible. Do not rely on document title weight.
    95	
